## OUTPUT FORMAT
{{.OutputFormatSnippet}}
{{- if .OutputSchemaSnippet}}
- `id`, `verdict`, `gate`, `priority`, `confidence_score`, and `remarks` are TOP-LEVEL keys of the JSON object; do NOT
  wrap them in a `verification` object
- `id` is the same UUID as the input `finding.id`; copy that actual UUID, never the `<uuid-v4>` placeholder
- `gate` names the decision-order gate that decided: one of `non-finding`,{{if .DiffScopeEnabled}} `diff-scope`,{{end}}
  `styleguide-contradiction`, `compile-error`, `confirm`, `refute`, `unverified`
- `verdict` is one of `confirmed`, `refuted`, `unverified` and MUST be the verdict the gate dictates:
  - `confirm` → `confirmed`
  - `unverified` → `unverified`
  - every other gate → `refuted`, even when the claim is technically real
- `priority` is an integer 0-3
- `confidence_score` is a number between 0 and 1 expressing your confidence in the verdict
- `remarks` is a short markdown explanation of the verdict; when `refuted` because an actual issue claim is false,
  MUST cite the concrete code or invariant that contradicts the finding
  - when `refuted` because the input is a non-finding, `remarks` MUST be exactly "no issue"
  - add paragraphs, e.g. an empty line, between distinct points to improve readability
  - put code references and symbol names in backticks or code blocks
  - format bold or italic when it makes sense to emphasize a point
- FINAL CONSISTENCY CHECK: if `remarks` says default compiler/type checker, `go build`, `go vet`, or equivalent
  tooling reports the finding's core issue, `gate` MUST be `compile-error` and `verdict` MUST be `refuted`; `confirm`
  is invalid in that case.
{{- if .DiffScopeEnabled}}
- `replacement_code_location` is TOP-LEVEL and always required:
  - set it to `null` when the submitted finding location already overlaps the diff or no valid replacement exists
  - otherwise set it to the full `code_location` of the exact causal diff line, copied from `find_lines`
{{- end}}
{{- end}}
